AutoDip Project Context
=======================

Overview
--------
AutoDip is a Django-based application and Python toolkit for automated urine dipstick analysis.
It currently supports:
1) Image upload and processing via web dashboard.
2) CV-style pad extraction (heuristic segmentation).
3) Rule/chart-based analyte interpretation for 10 dipstick pads.
4) Report generation as downloadable PDF.
5) Data persistence in Django models/admin.
6) Experimental per-analyte machine-learning classifiers with scikit-learn.

Repository Structure
--------------------
- `autodip/`
  - `cv.py`: extracts pad-level RGB data from strip images.
  - `workflow.py`: interprets extracted pad colors into medical levels.
  - `report.py`: creates a single-page PDF report.
  - `ml_classifier.py`: scikit-learn utilities for per-analyte model training/eval/prediction.
  - `cli.py`: project CLI entrypoints (if used externally).
- `lab/` (Django app)
  - `models.py`: stores uploaded tests/results/report path.
  - `views.py`: dashboard and detail pages.
  - `services.py`: orchestrates extract -> interpret -> report -> save.
  - `forms.py`: upload form config.
  - `templates/lab/dashboard.html`: upload UI + recent tests.
  - `templates/lab/detail.html`: per-test result details.
- `autodip_project/`: Django project settings/urls/wsgi/asgi.
- `tests/`: workflow and dashboard tests.
- `sample_training_data.json`: sample ML training set.

Current End-to-End Flow
-----------------------
1. User uploads an image on `/` dashboard.
2. `lab.services.process_dip_test` runs:
   - `autodip.cv.extract_cv_payload` -> obtains 10 pad RGB values.
   - `autodip.workflow.run_interpretation` -> maps RGB to analyte levels/statuses.
   - `autodip.report.generate_report` -> writes PDF summary.
   - Persists status/results/report on `DipTest`.
3. User opens detail page `/tests/<id>/` to review results and download PDF.

Analytes Covered
----------------
The 10-pad workflow supports:
- glucose
- protein
- ketone
- blood
- nitrite
- leukocytes
- bilirubin
- urobilinogen
- ph
- specific_gravity

Interpretation Strategy (Current)
---------------------------------
`autodip/workflow.py` uses analyte-specific color reference charts (`CHARTS`) and
matching utilities to assign classes, confidence, and metadata.
Outputs include fields like:
- `value`
- `measured_value`
- `status`
- `confidence`
- `distance`
- `clinical_note`

ML Classifier Module (Experimental)
-----------------------------------
`autodip/ml_classifier.py` provides a simple, separate ML path:
- One model per analyte.
- Feature set includes:
  - RGB channels
  - HSV channels
  - RGB ratios (R/G, R/B, G/B)
  - brightness
- Supported algorithms:
  - random_forest
  - svm
  - logistic_regression
- Main functions:
  - `rgb_to_hsv(rgb)`
  - `extract_features(rgb)`
  - `train_analyte_models(samples, algorithm=...)`
  - `evaluate_models(samples, algorithm=...)`
  - `predict_level(models, analyte, rgb)`

Data Format for ML
------------------
Sample records use:
{
  "analyte": "glucose",
  "rgb": [245, 222, 179],
  "label": "negative"
}

`sample_training_data.json` includes 50 synthetic-style samples (5 per analyte)
for quick experimentation.

Tests
-----
Primary tests currently in repo:
- `tests/test_dashboard.py`
  - validates upload flow and PDF artifact generation.
- `tests/test_workflow.py`
  - validates interpretation behavior and selected calibration cases.

How to Run Locally
------------------
Setup:
- `python -m pip install -r requirements.txt`
- `python manage.py migrate`
- `python manage.py runserver`

Run tests:
- `python manage.py test tests.test_workflow tests.test_dashboard -v 2`

Run ML demo:
- `python -m autodip.ml_classifier sample_training_data.json random_forest`

Known Constraints / Notes
-------------------------
- CV pad extraction in `autodip/cv.py` is heuristic and not camera-robust.
- Chart-based mapping can still be sensitive to lighting, white balance,
  and strip manufacturer color variance.
- ML module is intended for iterative improvement and requires real labeled data
  for strong generalization and reliable >90% production accuracy.

